data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 11 (EF Core 11), the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` will throw `InvalidOperationException` — there is no longer a configuration workaround.

The Cosmos DB SDK is inherently async, and EF Core previously wrapped it with sync-over-async shims. That escape hatch is now gone.

## How to fix it

Convert all synchronous calls to their async counterparts:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`, renamed with `Async` suffix
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`

You'll also need to propagate `async/await` up through your callers (controllers, services, etc.), which is the bulk of the migration effort.
